When you have a certificate file (.pem file), you usually add it to a keystore, but not convert it.

In order to add a certificate to a keystore (new/existing), you can run this `keytool` command:

&gt; keytool -importcert -keystore &quot;KEYSTORE_FILE&quot; -storepass &quot;KEYSTORE_PASSWORD&quot; -file &quot;CERTIFICATE_FILE&quot; -alias &quot;CERTIFICATE_ALIAS&quot;

Add a hidden input property to the model that you base the views on:

    [HiddenInput]
    public string Client { get; set; }

Then add it at the beginning of the form in all the views:

    @Html.HiddenFor(m =&gt; m.Client)

Now, in the controller, you can assign the client value to the `Client` property when building the model in the `GET` action, and check it for the decision you want to make in your `POST` action.

**UPDATE** If you don&#39;t want to add an extra property to the model, you can use `ViewBag` to hold the value (though the model solution above is better). In the controller, you can assign the client value in the `GET` action:

    ViewBag.Client = client;

Then add it at the beginning of the form in all the views:

    &lt;input type=&quot;hidden&quot; name=&quot;Client&quot; value=&quot;@ViewBag.Client&quot; /&gt;

And then check it for the decision you want to make in your `POST` action. Since it is not part of your model, you&#39;ll have to get it separately:

    public IActionResult PostAction(MyModel mode, string client) {
      switch(client) {
      //...
      }
    }

Note: the method above, allows you to use the same view for more than one client, essentially allowing you to create a kind of client groups or types. But if you actually have a different view for each client, then you don&#39;t need to pass a value by `ViewBag` and you can hard code it directly in each view:

    &lt;input type=&quot;hidden&quot; name=&quot;Client&quot; value=&quot;Client1&quot; /&gt;

The `HttpMethod` property on the `HttpRequest` object will get it for you. You can use this in your Controller:

    using System.Net.Http;
    
    if (HttpContext.Request.HttpMethod == HttpMethod.Post.Method)
     {
     // The action is a post method
     }

If you would like to find which `View` has called an action method, you can use the following in your `Url.Action` :

    @Path.GetFileNameWithoutExtension(Server.MapPath(VirtualPath))


An example call could be:

    @Url.Action(&quot;Action&quot;,&quot;Controller&quot;,new{callingView=Path.GetFileNameWithoutExtension(Server.MapPath(VirtualPath))})
     
You would need add a parameter to your controller method:

    public ActionResult Action(MyModel model, string callingView)

You can read more about `@VirtualPath` [here][1]


  [1]: https://stackoverflow.com/questions/6311463/how-to-get-the-current-view-name-in-asp-net-mvc-3

